# -*- lammps -*-
#
# In the third LJ example, we consider a thermostat theme using Langevan damping

units           lj
atom_style      atomic
boundary	p p p
lattice         sc 0.1
variable T equal 0.75
region          myregion block 0 10 0 10 0 10
create_box      1 myregion
create_atoms    1 box
mass            1 1.0
velocity        all create $T 87287
pair_style      lj/sf 2.5 # default cutoff
pair_coeff	1 1 1.0 1.0 2.5 # the last number overrides the cutoff
neighbor        0.3 bin
neigh_modify    every 20 delay 0 check yes

# The Langevin equation characterizes a particle undergoing Brownian
# motion in a viscous fluid.  It is a device to 'coax' the system to
# reach equilibrium faster.

# In LAMMPS, the integration of equations of motion are done by the "fix nve" command.
# The Langevin parameters are

# [initial T] [final T} [damping coefficient in time units] [random number seed]

fix		F1 all nve/limit 0.1
fix		lang all langevin $T $T 10.0 10235

dump    I all image 1000 *.jpg type type size 1000 1000 view 60 120
dump_modify I backcolor white boxcolor black
dump_modify I adiam 1 0.25
dump    M all movie 50 out.mp4 type type size 1000 1000 view 60 120
dump_modify M backcolor white boxcolor black
dump_modify M adiam 1 0.25

thermo		100
thermo_style	custom step temp pe ke etotal

# In this example we introduce a statement requesting LAMMPS to
# provide 'trajectory' data, inthis case,

# [fix label (D1)] [all particles] [customized statement]
# ...and output [particle ID] [track atoms] [xyz coordinates]

dump D1 all custom 1000 atom.dat id type x y z

run		10000

# When the run is complete, the file atom.dat has atomic coordinates
# for each specified time interval (in this case 1000).
